        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-27T19:46:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "why CommandList type is public in the first place? int64SliceFlag is internal and that\u0027s right.\nMaking CommaList internal would be even more cheaper.\n\nthis is inconsistent with other flag types. I don\u0027t see anything specific enough in \"comma-separated list\" format to require inconsistency",
      "parentUuid": "b2eb74db_8067df2b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 26,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 4
      },
      "revId": "d9df298682cc8dc9254f67a2255f1cc90c6a11c9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1eaf3d66_11946f6c",
        "filename": "common/flag/commalist.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 1161844
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-27T21:13:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Andrii, if I understand correctly your argument is that the current interface is more complex.  It is not, it is basically the same:\n\n var s []int64\n flag.Var(Int64Slice(\u0026s), \"blah\", \"blah\")\n\n var s []string\n flag.Var(NewCommaList(\u0026s), \"blah\", \"blah\")\n\nI think you are also arguing that it is more complex to implement.  It\u0027s like three or four more lines of very simple code, I don\u0027t think completely cutting off future extensibility is worth saving three lines of code.\n\nNodir, because Golang best practice is to return concrete types rather than interfaces.  flag.Value which is returned by the others is an interface.  Because interfaces are satisfied implicitly, there\u0027s basically no functional difference, see my example above.\n\nHowever, concrete types can be extended while still satisfying the interface.  But you can\u0027t retroactively add methods or fields to flag.Value.",
      "parentUuid": "7dfc4317_097ed389",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 26,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 4
      },
      "revId": "d9df298682cc8dc9254f67a2255f1cc90c6a11c9",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "529afd69_2422b3a6",
        "filename": "common/flag/commalist.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 26,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-27T21:57:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I understand the argument about returning concrete types, but the reasons behind do not quite apply here. There is no reason to expose the impl of the interface in the first place. There is no function diff, but there is more complexity: increased API surface, increased number of exported symbols, the length of index of godoc page is longer that necessary, a godoc reader has to read more. Exporting the concrete type adds complexity without adding any value, thus it is worse.\n\nWhy would we add methods or fields to CommaList? It has a single purpose/responsibility. We\u0027d need to add more fields or methods only iff we increase its responsibility scope, which would\u0027t be bad in the first place.",
      "parentUuid": "1eaf3d66_11946f6c",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 26,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 26,
        "endChar": 4
      },
